nodes.title: Prompt Note
widgets_values:
*Positive Prompt: Write as usual, specify minute details, the elements are usually changed during the render, also you can try to use same keywords multiple times but same meaning ( Eg: blue jeans, blue color jeans, jeans of blue color) to reduce major changes. 

Using the word multiple times increase it's strength.
Avoid writing multiple color words. A prompt which has "black" keyword written x3 will darken the image x3


If you weight the keywords like "(this:1.9), it may produce glitchy result. Avoid high weights.

*Negative Prompt: Write as usual, Sometimes Negative prompts causes noise in images, try reducing the use of embeddings if you encounter them. 

If your images are not looking according to the style for example, 2d cartoon SD models still produce 3d looking cartoons, they are because of negative embeddings, remove them.

nodes.title: Traveller Note
widgets_values:
*Enable the Traveller from above blue node, and Unmute the prompt travel group to use it, 

*First box is the changing prompt box formatted as - 
 "Frame Number" : "Changing Keyword",

*Second Box is the Normal positive prompt box, enter the text which will not change throughout the frames

*Third box is optional, ignore it. 
_________________________________________________________

1) Frame Number: Use at least 15 - 20 frames increase for a noticeable change.
2) Changing Keyword: Use minimum words (2-10) here, large sentences may give token error. 

3) Make Sure there is a comma in the last to separate the keyframes
For Eg- 

"0" :" Nature ",
"50" :" Ocean, Water",
"100" :"Fire",
"150" :"Nature"
 
150th key frame has no comma in the end.

nodes.title: CFG
widgets_values:
Sampler CFG - Use Between 4 - 9, Higher values cause artifacts, color noise, and weird backgrounds. Default value is 6. 

Refiner's CFG will increase 20% automatically.

nodes.title: HigheRes Fix | Detail Enhancer
widgets_values:
Total Sampler Steps: Total Number of steps for ksampler. (Default value - 26) 

Stop raw at nth step: Raw sampler will stop at this step.  (Default Value - 13)

HighRes Fix Upscale - It upscales the Latent - (value around 1.1 - 1.4 is good, above 1.5 no change is observed)
(Default Value - 1.2 which is good, it will be enhanced in the refiner workflow)

Start Highres Fix from nth step: Higres fix sampler will start at this step and continue till the total sampler steps. (Default Value - 12)


----------------------
Steps Theory: 
 
Total Steps - 30 iterations.
Raw Steps - First 14 Iterations.
High Res Steps - From 15th to 30th iteration. (1 overlapping iteration for good blending)  
________________________________________________________________________________________


Detail Enhancer - It injects noise in the model, use up to max value of 20 - Higer values cause micro details into morphing/sliding.

nodes.title: Batch Range Note
widgets_values:
Set The Max Frames your PC can handle at a time. This value should be same throughout the Batches.

*IMP If you use overlap then Batch Range and Overlap will add up to give Final Range

For Example: 
Batch Range = 50
Overlap = 10

Final Range = 60 (50+10) 
-------------------------------------------------------------

This Final Range will be changed in the last batch, it may increase or decrease during the last batch. This Auto Adjusting is to prevent last batch becoming too small (min 10) for AnimateDiff to render.

nodes.title: Lap Counter Node
widgets_values:
Lap Needed Box will show how much Times you need to click the "Queue Prompt". 
Change the Lap Counter to Increment for Final Rendering.

The Rendering System is Now Automated like CN Passes Extractor File. 
It will calculate skip frames value automatically, no need to enter now. 
Also, it will automatically Stop with the "Out of Frames" Error when Done rendering. 

It is calculated like this: 

*Skip Frame = Lap Counter x Range


IMP: The Last Lap will adjust automatically decrease or increase the remaining Frames.
The "Total Frames (T.F.) " is equal to the Images in CN 2 Directory 

For Example:  You have total Frames of 152, Range = 50, Overlap = 0,
So, it will run 4 Times 

[Math.Ceil(TF/Range) which will give 4 laps] 

Lap 1: Skip = 000 | Range = 50
Lap 2: Skip = 050 | Range = 50
Lap 3: Skip = 100 | Range = 52 <- 02 Remaining frames are auto adjusted here
Lap 4: Skip = 150 | Range = 00 <- It will give Out of Frame error and Stop


--------------------------------------


If somehow, A batch is skipped due to out of frame error, you can easily render it. 
Go to the explorer and check all the batch naming, if you found some missing, Change the Lap Counter to Fixed. 

Suppose my Batch_0005 is missing from the raw folder, then I'll set it to 5 and render ... easy as that.

nodes.title: Overlap Note
widgets_values:
Set Overlapping Frames. This value should be same throughout the Batches. 

*IMP: It should NOT be Greater than Batch Range. 

It can be 0 if you don't want any overlapping. 

Use values - 5, 10 or 20 to have a smooth Transition between two Batches. 

*IMP --- > If using overlap, Please Use Seam Fixer Workflow after rendering all frames to make it seamless transition between batches.

nodes.title: ControlNet Note
widgets_values:
● Lower Strength and End Percent can lead to creative results which will reduce the original image look (Applicable in Softedge, Canny, Depth, and LineArt Pass) and give more stylized look, close resemblance to the prompts.

● Greater Start percent around 0.3-0.5 tends to create a still image from the main prompt first and then an artifact character overlayed on it.  This Can be used for Abstract creation.

● Use Ip2p controlnet to have closer to original but different colors or elements. Also Adjust CFG. Lower Cfg (1-2) small change, Higher Cfg (4-7) Great change in the image adhering to the prompt.

By using mask, you can have more dynamic background animation, which was not possible in v.2 versions because of controlnet effect on backgrounds.

nodes.title: #2 Animation Raw v4.5 - No LCM
widgets_values:
HOW TO USE: 

1) Choose Model checkpoint you want to use
2) Enter Width and Height of your Output Image 
3) Choose Positive Prompts, you want to see in the output
4) Choose Loras, (You have to experiment which looks good or not)
5) Paste the Passes Directories in ControlNets (1 and 2) Loaders and set their models and weight (See Neon Purple note) also you can use CN mask for dynamic animated background.


6) Paste the path of Masks and Original Image.
7) Paste The Directory where you want to save the Images in the Output Save Directory Node
8) Select Batch Range (Number of images you want to render in one Queue) and Overlap Value.

9) Set Denoise Values of Foreground and Background. Masks are important here. (See notes near ksmapler) 
 

10) Batch Naming is Automated now.
11) Skip Frame is also Automated now.
12) After All the batches are rendered it's Ready for #3 Refiner workflow

 
*Special Features are separated in different files due to technical limitation, if combined in one file it will give dimensions errors if used in parallel :D


________________________________________

Main Download Folder Link : https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1HoZxKUX7WAg7ObqP00R4oIv48sXCEryQ?usp=sharing
_________________________________________

Update Log: Version 2 - Dec 23 

1) The weird color bleed/tint in the final images is removed by LCM technique (Found Experimentally) in this workflow. 

*A yellow tint may be observed (In low cfg) with TemporalDiff model in the final output which can be removed easily in post processing by using curves > blue channel >playing with the curve.   

2) LCM now supported, will have 2x - 3x Render speed with higher batch range input, as lcm uses under 10 steps, you 2x input the batch range and image resolution. 

3) Added Batch Number Naming for organizing
4) Added Output Save Location Path
5) Added bunch of custom nodes for more efficiency and organizing. (See installation List)

* In prompts experiment with extreme words, and also test with loras with low strength. 
* Background still has weird artifacts. Play with sampler cfg (1-6) to see some change.
* IP adaptor produces messy results with LCM

nodes.title: OUT OF MEMORY ERROR
widgets_values:
If you got out of memory Error while it reaches the above sampler, then See the "Requested Memory:  xx MB" in the red error box.

If that xx memory requested is below 1GB then just queue the prompt again, the workflow will just run fine. It will take CPU's Ram to Render. 

If it's above 1GB then lower the Resolution and then queue to run it smoothly or use smaller batch range.

nodes.title: Subject and Background Denoising note
widgets_values:
● Subject : Set denoise from 0.3 - 0.8, for consistent character of the original. Use Value 1 to create a new. 



● Background : Set denoise from 0.1 - 0.3 to have a stable and similar to original background. Use value 1 to create a new. 


● Inpainting - Set Subject to 1.0 and Background 0.0 to have a inpainting render.



IMP: DO NOT CHANGE DENOISE VALUE IN THE BELOW KSAMPLER. 
Leave it at 1. if you lower it, say to 0.5 then it will half the above subject and background denoising values.
